🚀 Day 5: Autoscaling (Scale Up → Scale Down)

  🔹 1. Enabled Autoscaling on MIG
      Went to: Google Cloud Console → Instance Group
      Configured:
      Min instances = 2
      Max instances = 4
      Target CPU = 60%
  
      👉 Purpose:
      Automatically adjust instances based on load
  
  🔹 2. Initial State (Before Load)
      Running instances = 2 (min size)
      CPU utilization = Low
      
      👉 System is stable but not under stress
  
  🔹 3. Generated Load (Traffic Simulation)
      Used Apache Benchmark:
      ab -n 10000 -c 150 http://<LB-IP>/
      
      👉 Simulates:
      10,000 total requests
      150 concurrent users
  
  🔹 4. Observed No Scaling (Important Learning)
      CPU remained < 60%
      Instances stayed at 2
      
      👉 Reason:
      Nginx is lightweight → CPU not stressed
  
  🔹 5. Forced CPU Load (Real Testing)
      Executed on VMs:
      yes > /dev/null &
      
      👉 Result:
      CPU usage ↑ (~100%)
      Sustained load created
  
  🔹 6. Scale-Up Triggered
      CPU crossed 60%
      MIG added instances
      
      👉 Instances:
      2 → 3 → 4
      
      👉 This proves:
      Autoscaling (scale-up) works
  
  🔹 7. Observed System Behavior
      New instances created automatically
      Load distributed via Load Balancer
      System handled increased demand
      🔹 8. Stopped Load (Cleanup)
      
      Executed:
      pkill yes
      
      👉 Result:
      CPU utilization ↓
  
  🔹 9. Scale-Down Triggered
      CPU dropped below threshold
      MIG reduced instances
      
      👉 Instances:
      4 → 2 (min size)
      
      👉 This proves:
      Autoscaling (scale-down) works
  
  🧠 Key Learnings
      Autoscaling is metric-driven (CPU-based)
      Traffic ≠ scaling trigger
      Sustained load is required  
      Nginx may not generate enough CPU load
      Scale-up and scale-down both are critical
